.TH "SUPPRESSEDERROR.SUPPRESSEDERROR" "3JS" "July 30, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
SuppressedError.SuppressedError \- SuppressedError() constructor
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]SuppressedError()\f[B]\f[R] constructor creates
\f[CR]SuppressedError\f[R] objects.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
new SuppressedError(error, suppressed)
new SuppressedError(error, suppressed, message)

SuppressedError(error, suppressed)
SuppressedError(error, suppressed, message)
.EE
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] \f[CR]SuppressedError()\f[R] can be called with or
without \f[CR]new\f[R].
Both create a new \f[CR]SuppressedError\f[R] instance.
.RE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]error\f[R]
The new error that results in the suppression of \f[CR]suppressed\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]suppressed\f[R]
The error that was originally thrown and is now suppressed.
.TP
\f[B]message\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An optional human\-readable description of the aggregate error.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] \f[CR]SuppressedError()\f[R] does not accept
\f[CR]options\f[R] like \f[CR]Error()\f[R] and other subclasses do,
because the semantics of \f[CR]cause\f[R] overlaps with
\f[CR]suppressed\f[R].
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Creating a SuppressedError
.IP
.EX
\f[B]try\f[R] {
  \f[B]throw\f[R] \f[B]new\f[R] SuppressedError(
    \f[B]new\f[R] Error(\(dqNew error\(dq),
    \f[B]new\f[R] Error(\(dqOriginal error\(dq),
    \(dqHello\(dq,
  );
} \f[B]catch\f[R] (e) {
  console.log(e.suppressed); \f[I]// Error: \(dqOriginal error\(dq\f[R]
  console.log(e.error); \f[I]// Error: \(dqNew error\(dq\f[R]
}
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\c
